    <h2>BWH - Security Details</h2>
    <h3>Are the BushWise Servers Secure? Can you trust us?</h3>
    <p>
    <a href='http://www.thawte.com' title='External Link: Thawte Secure Site' target='_blank'><img src='imgs/security/thawteLogo.gif' alt='Thawte Secure Site' width='144' height='51' class='imgL' /></a>
    All the BushWise servers are designed and configured to securely transmit<sup>1</sup> any sensitive data that you input during any commercial transactions or logged-in administrative tasks. Examine your Browser status bar and, on the appropriate pages, you should see an indication that the transaction is secure ( usually in the form of a &#8220;locked&#8221; padlock icon ). If this is the case, your personal information ( and any other data including Credit Card details ) will be securely encrypted for transmission over the Internet.
    </p><p>
    <span class='smTxt'>1: We use Thawte as our preferred agent for <acronym title='Secure Socket Layer'>SSL</acronym> digital certificates on all our servers.</span>
    </p>
    <h4>How do you know they are secure? The following are two references:</h4>
    <p>
    Please read them if you are concerned about leaving us your Credit Card details or other sensitive data.
    </p>
    <ul>
    <li>
      The <a href='http://www-genome.wi.mit.edu/WWW/faqs/www-security-faq.html' title='External Link: The WWW Security FAQ' target='_blank'>WWW Security FAQ</a> <span class='smTxt'>-- ( External Link )</span>
    </li><li>
      The <a href='http://www.thawte.com/support/crypto/contents.html' title='External Link: The Thawte Security FAQ' target='_blank'>Thawte Security FAQ</a> <span class='smTxt'>-- ( External Link )</span>
    </li>
    </ul>
    <h4>How does it all work? ( <i>technical information</i> )</h4>
    <p>
    <acronym title='Secure Socket Layer'>SSL</acronym> uses public-key encryption to exchange a session key between the client and server; this session key is used to encrypt the <acronym title='HyperText Transport Protocol'>HTTP</acronym> transaction ( both request and response ). Each transaction uses a different session key so that if someone manages to decrypt a transaction, that does not mean that they've found the server's secret key; if they want to decrypt another transaction, they'll need to spend as much time and effort on the second transaction as they did on the first.
    </p><p>
    Most modern Browsers do encryption using either a 40-bit secret key or a 128-bit secret key. Many people feel that using a 40-bit key is insecure because it's vulnerable to a &#8220;brute force&#8221; attack ( trying each of the 2^40 possible keys until you find the one that decrypts the message ). However, we at BushWise use a 128-bit key therefore eliminating this problem because there are 2^128 instead of 2^40 possible keys.
    </p>
